Lemma 2. I(M,Î”) over-approximates the set of models Mâ€² that can be obtained from M via Î”.

Lemma 2 states that I(M,Î”) contains all models that can be obtained from Î” and possibly more, but not fewer (see Appendix A for proofs) . For some values of ğ‘, the interval abstraction may cease to be an over-approximation and encode exactly the models that can be obtained from M via Î”, e.g., when ğ‘ = âˆ.
A model shift ğ‘†, although plausible, may result in changes to the classi cation of the original input ğ‘¥. When this happens, robustness of explanations becomes vacuous. For this reason, we will focus on sound shifts, formulated as follows.

De nition 13. Consider an input ğ‘¥ âˆˆ R ğ‘0 and an FFNN M s.t. M(ğ‘¥) = ğ‘. Let I(M,Î”) be the interval abstraction of M under a set of plausible model shifts Î”. We say that Î” is sound if I(M,Î”)(ğ‘¥) = ğ‘.
We are now ready to formally de ne the CFX robustness property that we target in this work.

De nition 14. Consider an input ğ‘¥ âˆˆ R ğ‘0 and an FFNN M s.t. M(ğ‘¥) = ğ‘. Let I(M,Î”) be the interval abstraction of M under a sound set of plausible model shifts Î”. We say that a CFX ğ‘¥â€² is Î”-robust i I(M,Î”)(ğ‘¥â€²) = 1 âˆ’ ğ‘.
We illustrate these concepts in the following example.
Example 3. We observe that the INN in Example 2 corresponds to the interval abstraction I(M,Î”) of the FFNN M in Example 1, obtained for Î” = {ğ‘† M âˆ’ ğ‘†(M) âˆ â‰¤ 0.1}.
The symbolic expressions for the outputs of the INN are:

