Â§5.2, we change the target_proba hypterparameter to values (0.55 - 0.95) lower than default (1.0) to optimise proximity while maintaining a high validity.
â€¢ Proto: we use the Alibi library implementation. Hyperparameters of this method are the default values.
â€¢ MILP: we implemented De nition 4 for neural networks, which is also a simpli ed version of Algorithm 5, [Mohammadi et al., 2021] satisfying the same plausibility constraints in support of heterogeneous datasets.
â€¢ ROAR: we use their open-sourced implementation: https://github.com/AI4LIFE-GROUP/ROAR. The hyperparameters are set to default values.
Evaluation metrics Similar to [Dutta et al., 2022], we use the sklearn implementation of local outlier factor: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn. neighbors.LocalOutlierFactor.html. Parameters are set to default.
Retraining and ğ›¿ values Our retraining procedure follows that of sklearnâ€™s MLPClassi er.partial_ t() function. ğ›¿ğ‘šğ‘ğ‘¥ in Â§5.2 (also the target ğ›¿ in Â§5.3) is obtained by the following procedures. Consider the base model trained on D1, M, and the dataset to retrain on, D2:
1. Obtain ğ›¿ğ‘ by retraining M on ğ‘% (initially ğ‘ = 1) of D2: randomly select ğ‘% instances from D2 and train on them. Repeat this step for 5 times and get 5 di erent retrained classi ers, Mğ‘–â€², ğ‘– âˆˆ [5]. Then, ğ›¿ğ‘ = ğ‘šğ‘ğ‘¥({ Mâˆ’Mğ‘–â€² ğ‘, ğ‘– âˆˆ [5], ğ‘ = âˆ}).
2. Test if model shift Î” built with ğ›¿ğ‘ is sound for at least 50 test instances in D1.
3. If the condition in step 2 is satis ed, increase ğ›¿ğ‘ and repeat step 1 and step 2; if not, ğ›¿ğ‘šğ‘ğ‘¥ = ğ›¿ğ‘.
In order to show how ğ›¿ğ‘ (obtained by step 1 above) changes as ğ‘ increases to 100%, we demonstrate the relationship under our settings in Figure 4. It is shown that ğ›¿ğ‘ values increase with slight uctuations as ğ‘ increases, and the magnitudes depend on the classi er and the dataset. As can be observed, ğ›¿100% values are always greater than ğ›¿ğ‘šğ‘ğ‘¥ , indicating that the model shifts obtained by retraining on 100% of D2 exceeds those included in Î” built with ğ›¿ğ‘šğ‘ğ‘¥ , as stated in Â§5.3. Indeed, observing the vm2 results of MILP-R from Table 1 again, we
nd CFXs that are 100% Î”-robust (as per Figures 2(e-h)) with a smaller ğ›¿ are likely to also be robust to certain instances of Î” with a larger ğ›¿.
D Applying Î”-Robustness as a Filter
Similar to evaluating robustness, our approach can also be used as a lter for provably robust CFXs when multiple CFXs

