corresponding Î” is sound. However, the fact that Î” is not sound for an instance ğ‘¥ means that there exist some model shifts in Î” under which the classi cation result of the test

13

instance will change, and in practice there could be only a few such model shifts. Therefore, it could be meaningful to also test such non-sound sets of model shifts, as is the case in this example. We observe that the number of robust CFXs decreases as model changes become larger. Our approach is able to lter out the non-robust CFXs at any given Î”. In reality, as stated in Â§1, the explanation-providing agent will have an estimate of typical ğ›¿ values retrained on certain amount of new data, and the time period to collect such new data. With our approach, the agent could select only the Î”-robust CFXs, and provide a better estimate of how long they are valid for.
E Hyperparameter Tuning for Base Methods
Concrete implementations of Step 4 in Algorithm 1 depend on each base methodsâ€™ tunable hyperparameters, and are di erent for Wachter et al.-R, Proto-R, and MILP-R. In this section we introduce detail Step 4 for each of these method.
Wachter et al. In the Alibi library implementation 6, the loss function of [Wachter et al., 2017] is:
ğ‘™(ğ‘¥, ğ‘¥â€²) = (ğœ(M(ğ‘¥â€²)), ğ‘¦ğ‘¡ )2 + ğœ†ğ¿1(ğ‘¥, ğ‘¥â€²)
where ğœ(M(ğ‘¥â€²)) is the value of the neural networkâ€™s output node and ğœ is the sigmoid function. ğœ(M(ğ‘¥â€²) can be interpreted as the probability of class 1. ğ‘¦ğ‘¡ is the target probability (of class 1) of the resulting CFX for Wachter et al.-R. In our setting where test instances are of class 0, ğ‘¦ğ‘¡ could take values [0.5, 1.0], the lower ğ‘¦ğ‘¡ is, the easier it is to nd a closer (measured by L1 metric) CFX. ğœ† is the weight term for proximity. We apply two nested outer loops in search of the optimal ğ‘¦ğ‘¡ and ğœ† values to nd robust CFXs. For each experiment, we start with the ğ‘¦ğ‘¡ value taken in the non-robust setting, increase ğ‘¦ğ‘¡ by 0.1 until it reaches 1.0. For each ğ‘¦ğ‘¡ to test, we try nding robust CFXs using ğœ† values of {0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2}, where 0.1 is the default value.
Proto. In the case of Proto, the loss term pertaining to prediction correctness in the Alibi library implementation is the di erence between the output probability of the desired class and the output probability of the undesired class plus ğœ… (default 0), a hyperparameter to control the impact of this loss term in the loss function. In Proto-R, we gradually increase ğœ… by 0.1 until it reaches 1.0 at each iteration.
MILP. For MILP, referring to De nition 4, the M(ğ‘¥â€²) = 1 âˆ’ ğ‘ condition requires that the lower bound of the output interval be greater than zero which, after the sigmoid output activation, corresponds to a probability greater than or equal to 0.5 for class 1. In this case, this method mostly nd CFXs that lie on the decision boundary of the classi er. In MILP-R, to increase the in uence of prediction con dence and relax the cost requirement, we require in the MILP encoding that the lower bound of the output interval be greater than ğœ–, ğœ– â‰¥ 0. At each iteration, we raise ğœ– by 0.2 until it reaches 20.
Concrete values of each of the parameters can be found in the experiments in the accompanying source codes.
